# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anna-kingsford
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anna-kingsford/a-breeze-harper] Harper attributes her initial interest in practicing veganism to the influence of the work of Dick Gregory in connecting diet to the liberation struggle of marginalized groups, and to Afrocentric, raw foodist Queen Afua.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-breeze-harper] In 2015, Harper organized a conference, *The Vegan Praxis of Black Lives Matters*, to discuss intersectional issues concerning veganism and the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-breeze-harper] In the same year, Harper joined the advisory board for *Black Vegans Rock*.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-breeze-harper] Harper was the Humane Party's vice-presidential nominee for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] In 1893, Cole prepared a set of vegetarian menus that received high commendation at the Universal Cookery Exhibition.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] The menus were later published as "Menus for a Week in November" in Rachel Swain's *Swain Cookery* and in Florence I.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] Nicholson's *The Jubilee Cookery Book: Vegetarian Recipes*.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] Cole worked in several London vegetarian organisations.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] Tovey in founding the Battersea, Clapham and Wandsworth Vegetarian Society, with A.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] She was a committee member of the Women's Vegetarian Union and gave a cookery lesson for the union at the offices of the Vegetarian Federal Union in 1898.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] According to James Gregory, Cole worked as an assistant to Nicholson and later to Charlotte Despard.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] She succeeded Nicholson as editor of *The Children's Realm*.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] By 1914, she was honorary secretary of the Vegetarian Federal Union.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] Cole gave public talks and demonstrations on vegetarian cookery.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] In 1910, as secretary of the West London Vegetarian Society, she gave a cookery demonstration at a vegetarian dinner held by the society at Pirbright Hall, Southfields.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] In 1913, as honorary secretary of the London Vegetarian Society, she spoke on "What is Vegetarianism" at a meeting at the Adult School in Sutton.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] In July 1915, *The Jewish Chronicle* published an interview with Cole, then secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, on vegetarianism and Jewish dietary practice.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] She argued that a vegetarian diet was compatible with Jewish religious observance and discussed food economy during the First World War.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] In 1917, when described as a former organising secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, she gave cookery demonstrations for the Food and Cookery Association in Southampton, where she presented vegetarian menus and methods for reducing food waste.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] Cole was listed as secretary of the Children's Dinner Fund in 1916.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] Hilda Kean writes that Nicholson established the fund for underfed children, distributing cheap meals of vegetable soup, wholemeal bread, and wholemeal currant bread.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-m-cole] In 1921, Cole was honorary secretary and organiser of the Women's Freedom League Settlement in Nine Elms, which provided daily penny and halfpenny hot meals for more than 100 children and operated a milk depot.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:anna-kingsford/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] He became a vegetarian as a young man through reading the work of T.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] Bailey Walker and joined the Vegetarian Society in 1877.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] He worked as an analytical chemist in Manchester and for James Woolley, Sons and Co., manufacture chemists.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] Duncan had studied with Carl Remigius Fresenius.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] He was also a Fellow of the Chemical Society.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] In 1884, Duncan authored a pamphlet *The Chemistry of Foods*.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] It was republished as *The Chemistry of Food and Nutrition* by the Vegetarian Society in 1905.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] Forward noted that Duncan had given "valuable aid to the Vegetarian Society in connection with the chemistry of food, and has contributed many useful essays and papers on the subject".
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] Duncan was on the executive committee of the Vegetarian Society in 1880 and later served as a vice-president.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] In 1899, Duncan commented that "a grain of wheat contains everything that is required for nutrition and these constituents are in the right proportion, so that were it necessary we could live on wheatmeal bread and water alone".
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] He later moved to New South Wales, Australia but remained in contact with vegetarians in England and was an officer for the Vegetarian Society in 1935.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] He married Annie Margaret Allison in 1890.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] They had two children: Frank and Phyllis.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] Duncan died in Punchbowl, New South Wales in 1946, aged 90.
[src:anna-kingsford/a-w-duncan] He was privately cremated at Rockwood crematorium.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She was one of the first English women to obtain a degree in medicine, after Elizabeth Garrett Anderson, and the only medical student at the time to graduate without having experimented on a single animal.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She pursued her degree in Paris, graduating in 1880 after six years of study, so that she could continue her animal advocacy from a position of authority.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Her final thesis, *L'Alimentation Végétale de l'Homme*, was on the benefits of vegetarianism, published in English as *The Perfect Way in Diet* (1881).
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She founded the Food Reform Society that year, travelling within the UK to talk about vegetarianism, and to Paris, Geneva, and Lausanne to speak out against animal experimentation.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford was interested in Buddhism and Gnosticism, and became active in the Theosophical movement in England, becoming president of the London Lodge of the Theosophical Society in 1883.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] In 1884 she founded the Hermetic Society, which lasted until 1887 when her health declined.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She said she received insights in trance-like states and in her sleep; these were collected from her manuscripts and pamphlets by her lifelong collaborator Edward Maitland, and published posthumously in the book, *Clothed with the Sun* (1889).
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Subject to ill-health all her life, she died of lung disease at the age of 41, brought on by a bout of pneumonia.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Her writing was virtually unknown for over 100 years after Maitland published her biography, *The Life of Anna Kingsford* (1896), though Helen Rappaport wrote in 2001 that her life and work are once again being studied.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford was born Annie Bonus on 16 September 1846 in Maryland Point, Stratford, to Elizabeth Ann Schröder and John Bonus, a wealthy merchant.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She was the youngest of seven children, with siblings Elizabeth, John, Henry, Albert, Edward, Joseph, and Charles William.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] A precocious child, she wrote her first poem at the age of nine and, at thirteen, completed a longer work, *Beatrice: a Tale of the Early Christians*.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Accounts of her early life also describe experiences that later informed her spiritual outlook.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Edward Maitland described her as a "born seer", attributing to her the ability to perceive apparitions and to intuit character and fortune, which she learned to keep private.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She also took part in foxhunting, but is said to have abandoned it after experiencing a vision of herself as the fox.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] By the late 1860s, Kingsford had begun to articulate her views on women's position in society.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] In an 1868 essay advocating female equality, she adopted the pseudonym "Ninon", invoking Ninon de l'Enclos, noted for her wit, independence, and intellectual reputation.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] In a letter of August 1873, also signed "Ninon", she explained: "much, you know is permitted to men which to women is forbidden.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She contributed articles to *Penny Post* between 1868 and 1873.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Supported by an annual income of £700 from her father, she purchased *The Lady's Own Paper* in 1872 and became its editor, a role that brought her into contact with prominent reformers, including the writer and anti-vivisectionist Frances Power Cobbe.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] An article by Cobbe on vivisection, published in the paper, prompted Kingsford's enduring interest in the subject.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford married her cousin, Algernon Godfrey Kingsford, on 31 December 1867, at the age of 21, shortly after reaching her legal majority.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] The match had previously been opposed by her family, who considered Algernon unsuitable due to his limited financial prospects and the social stigma surrounding his father's suicide.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] The fact that he was also her cousin, while legally permitted in Victorian England, attracted additional social scrutiny.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] The timing of the marriage is significant.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] By waiting until she had reached legal adulthood, Kingsford was able to proceed without parental control and to negotiate the terms of the union herself.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Before the marriage, Algernon agreed that she would retain personal autonomy and be free to pursue intellectual and professional work.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] These terms were supported by her independent income, inherited from her father, which remained legally her own and outside her husband's control.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] This financial independence gave her a degree of freedom that was unusual for women of her time.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] The couple settled in Lichfield, where Algernon was preparing for Anglican orders.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] In 1868, Kingsford gave birth to their only child, a daughter, Eadith.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] The pregnancy was difficult, and her health declined afterward.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Within the household, responsibilities developed in ways that diverged from prevailing Victorian norms: Algernon assumed responsibility for managing the household and its staff, while Kingsford increasingly directed her efforts toward writing, reform work, and later medical study.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] The conjugal aspect of the marriage appears to have been limited.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] According to later accounts, particularly those of Edward Maitland, the couple came to live as brother and sister.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Taken together, these elements indicate that the marriage functioned less as a conventional domestic partnership and more as a structured arrangement that supported Kingsford's work.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Her independent financial position, combined with agreed terms and a reconfiguration of household roles, enabled her to pursue a public and professional life that would otherwise have been difficult within the constraints of Victorian society.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She converted to Roman Catholicism in 1870, despite her husband's position as an Anglican clergyman.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] In 1873, Kingsford met the writer Edward Maitland, a widower, who shared her rejection of materialism.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] With the blessing of Kingsford's husband, the two began to collaborate, Maitland accompanying her to Paris when she decided to study medicine.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Paris was at that time the center of a revolution in the study of physiology, much of it as a result of experiments on animals, particularly dogs, and mostly conducted without anaesthetic.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Claude Bernard (1813–1878), described as the "father of physiology", was working there, and famously said that "the physiologist is not an ordinary man: he is a scientist, possessed and absorbed by the scientific idea he pursues.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Walter Gratzer, professor emeritus of biochemistry at King's College London, writes that significant opposition to vivisection emerged in Victorian England, in part in revulsion at the research being conducted in France.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Bernard and other well-known physiologists, such as Charles Richet in France and Michael Foster in England, were strongly criticized for their work.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] British anti-vivisectionists infiltrated the lectures in Paris of François Magendie, Bernard's teacher, who dissected dogs without anaesthesia, allegedly shouting at them—"Tais-toi, pauvre bête!" (*Shut up, you poor beast!*) — while he worked.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Bernard's wife, Marie-Francoise Bernard, was violently opposed to his research, though she was financing it through her dowry.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] In the end, she divorced him and set up an anti-vivisection society.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] This was the atmosphere in the faculty of medicine and the teaching hospitals in Paris when Kingsford arrived, shouldering the additional burden of being a woman.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Although women were allowed to study medicine in France, Rudacille writes that they were not welcomed.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford was distraught over the sights and sounds of the animal experiments she saw.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford adopted a vegetarian diet on the advice of her brother John Bonus.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She was a vice-president of the Vegetarian Society.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Alan Pert, one of her biographers, wrote that Kingsford was caught in torrential rain in Paris in November 1886 on her way to the laboratory of Louis Pasteur, one of the most prominent vivisectionists of the period.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She reportedly spent hours in wet clothing and developed pneumonia, then pulmonary tuberculosis.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She travelled to the Riviera and Italy, sometimes with Maitland, at other times with her husband, hoping in vain that a different climate would help her recover.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] In July 1887, she settled in London in a house she and her husband rented at 15 Wynnstay Gardens, Kensington, and waited to die, although she remained mentally active.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] She died on 22 February 1888, aged 41, and was buried in the churchyard of Saint Eata's, an 11th-century church in Atcham by the River Severn, her husband's church.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Her name at death is recorded as Annie Kingsford.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] On her marriage in Sussex in 1867, her name was given as Annie Bonus.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford's writings on animal ethics address vivisection, vegetarianism, and the moral status of non-human life.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford's work in this area reflects her engagement with women's political rights and broader social reform movements.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Her early and literary writings include poetry and prose fiction, often incorporating religious and symbolic themes.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] These works address bodily health, hygiene, and dietary practice, often in relation to ethical and spiritual concerns.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] Kingsford's theological writings explore mysticism, symbolism, and alternative interpretations of Christian doctrine.
[src:anna-kingsford/anna-kingsford] These shorter works include periodical writing and contributions to edited volumes.
